import{_ as e,o as t,c as a,a as r}from"./app-136a9036.js";const o={},i=r('<h1 id="_1" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#_1" aria-hidden="true">#</a> 1</h1><h2 id="ru-verbs" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#ru-verbs" aria-hidden="true">#</a> <em>ru-verbs</em></h2><p>ru-verbs means that you add the suffix &#39;る&#39; after verb base, just like:</p><blockquote><p>a. 食べ -&gt; 食べる</p><p>b. 起き -&gt; 起きる</p></blockquote><p>a. means eat, when we conjugation it into <em>tabaru</em>, the status of the word has changed; But the base doesn&#39;t change.</p><p><em>tabaru</em> still means eat, but the status changed into &#39;to eat&#39;.</p><p>Th vowels <em>a</em>,<em>u</em>, or <em>o</em> right before &quot;る&quot;，it must be <em>ru-verbs</em> except irregular verbs.</p><h2 id="u-verbs" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#u-verbs" aria-hidden="true">#</a> <em>u-verbs</em></h2><p>then, the <em>ru-verbs</em> means the word add a suffix &#39;る&#39;, so <em>u-verbs</em> could also mean the word add a suffix &#39;う&#39;?</p><p>the answer is : definily no.</p><p><em>u-verbs</em> means in the conjugation the letter will switching in the same row of <em>hiragana</em> chart, just like:</p><blockquote><p>a. 行く -&gt; 行き</p><p>b. 飲む -&gt; 飲み</p></blockquote><p>in a. we could learn that く just simply switching into き, whatever く and き, both of their conjugation is happening in the か row of the <em>hiragana</em> chart.</p><p>in b. , the む switching into み just basic happened in the ま row of the <em>hiragana</em> chart.</p><h2 id="the-dictionary-form" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#the-dictionary-form" aria-hidden="true">#</a> The &quot;dictionary form&quot;</h2><p>the dictionary form not restricted that the the bases form from dictionary, it just mean a lot of dictionary will show you the form like する or くる when you search the dictionary for &#39;to do&#39; or &#39;to come&#39;.</p><h2 id="the-present-tense-affirmative-forms" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#the-present-tense-affirmative-forms" aria-hidden="true">#</a> The present tense affirmative forms</h2><p>it is means that some words have the same meaning with dictionary form but spread positive meaning, just like：</p><blockquote><p>食べます　(i&#39;m) to eat</p></blockquote><h2 id="the-present-tense-negative-forms" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#the-present-tense-negative-forms" aria-hidden="true">#</a> The present tense negative forms</h2><p>it is means that some words have the same meaning with dictionary form but spread positive meaning, just like:</p><blockquote><p>食べません (i&#39;m) not to eat</p></blockquote><h2 id="stems" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#stems" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Stems</h2><p>The bases with <em>ru-verbs</em>, and bases plus <em>i</em> with <em>u-verbs</em>, just like:</p><blockquote><p>し</p><p>き</p></blockquote><h2 id="inrregular-verbs" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#inrregular-verbs" aria-hidden="true">#</a> &quot;inrregular verbs&quot;</h2><p>We have knew <em>ru-verbs</em> and <em>u-verbs</em> at the beggining, but here are some conjugations outside of them, just like:</p><blockquote><p>する -&gt; します (to do)</p><p>くる -&gt; きます (to come)</p></blockquote><p>These 2 verbs normally as a suffix, like ’勉強する’.</p><ul class="contains-task-list"><li class="task-list-item"><input class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="" type="checkbox"> The vowels are different from the dictionary forms, but why?</li></ul><hr><h2 id="how-to-memorize-these-conjugation" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#how-to-memorize-these-conjugation" aria-hidden="true">#</a> How to memorize these conjugation?</h2><p>Just make these verbs as a set, to memory both of the dictionary form and present affirmative form.</p>',33),s=[i];function h(n,m){return t(),a("div",null,s)}const u=e(o,[["render",h],["__file","1.html.vue"]]);export{u as default};
